[bj 0718]\n\n        :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the\n            simulation. Call the CMR_IA.make_params() function to get a\n            dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.\n        :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be\n            presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number\n            of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to\n            range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity\n            matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to\n            zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length. If presenting word pairs, should be 3D array.\n        :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all\n            words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must\n            match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along\n            row k-1 and column k-1.\n        :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat\n            should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The\n            matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial\n            position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source\n            features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the\n            kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)\n        :param rec_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are recalled\n            by the real subjects in a free recall phase on each trial. The rows are\n            corresponding to pres_mat"". Used in simulating PEERS recognition. (DEFAULT=None)\n        :param ffr_mat: A 1D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are recalled\n            by the real subjects in a final free recall phase. Used in simulating\n            PEERS recognition. (DEFAULT=None)\n        :param cue_mat: A 1D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are presented\n            to the model in recognition and cued recall. If presenting word pairs, should be 2D array. (DEFAULT=None)\n        :param task: A string indicating the type of task to simulate. 'FR': free recall; \n            'CR': cued recall; 'Recog': recognization; 'Success': successive tests. (DEFAULT='FR')\n        :param mode: A string indicating the type of task mode to simulate. \n            For task = 'FR', 'IFR': immediate free recall; 'DFR': delayed recall.\n            For task = 'CR', 'Simultaneous': simultaneous encoding; 'Sequential': sequential encoding.\n            For task = 'Recog', 'Continuous': continuous recognition; 'Final': recognition in final stage. \n            For task = 'Success', 'Recog-CR': test1 recognition, test2 cued recall; 'Recog-Recog': test1 & test2 both recognition; 'CR-Recog': test1 cued recall, test2 recognition; 'CR-CR': test1 & test2 both cued recall. (DEFAULT='IFR')\n        : param test1_num: An integer indicating how many items are tested in test1 during \n            successitve tests. (DEFAULT=None)\n        ";

 0079:         """
 0080:         Initializes a CMR2 object and prepares it to simulate the session defined
 0081:         by pres_mat. [bj 0718]
 0082: 
 0083:         :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the
 0084:             simulation. Call the CMR_IA.make_params() function to get a
 0085:             dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.
 0086:         :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be
 0087:             presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number
 0088:             of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to
 0089:             range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity
 0090:             matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to
 0091:             zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length. If presenting word pairs, should be 3D array.
 0092:         :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all
 0093:             words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must
 0094:             match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along
 0095:             row k-1 and column k-1.
 0096:         :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat
 0097:             should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The
 0098:             matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial
 0099:             position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source
 0100:             features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the
 0101:             kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)
 0102:         :param rec_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are recalled
 0103:             by the real subjects in a free recall phase on each trial. The rows are
 0104:             corresponding to pres_mat. Used in simulating PEERS recognition. (DEFAULT=None)
 0105:         :param ffr_mat: A 1D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are recalled
 0106:             by the real subjects in a final free recall phase. Used in simulating
 0107:             PEERS recognition. (DEFAULT=None)
 0108:         :param cue_mat: A 1D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are presented
 0109:             to the model in recognition and cued recall. If presenting word pairs, should be 2D array. (DEFAULT=None)
 0110:         :param task: A string indicating the type of task to simulate. 'FR': free recall; 
 0111:             'CR': cued recall; 'Recog': recognization; 'Success': successive tests. (DEFAULT='FR')
 0112:         :param mode: A string indicating the type of task mode to simulate. 
 0113:             For task = 'FR', 'IFR': immediate free recall; 'DFR': delayed recall.
 0114:             For task = 'CR', 'Simultaneous': simultaneous encoding; 'Sequential': sequential encoding.
 0115:             For task = 'Recog', 'Continuous': continuous recognition; 'Final': recognition in final stage. 
 0116:             For task = 'Success', 'Recog-CR': test1 recognition, test2 cued recall; 'Recog-Recog': test1 & test2 both recognition; 'CR-Recog': test1 cued recall, test2 recognition; 'CR-CR': test1 & test2 both cued recall. (DEFAULT='IFR')
 0117:         : param test1_num: An integer indicating how many items are tested in test1 during 
 0118:             successitve tests. (DEFAULT=None)
 0119:         """

static char __pyx_doc_6CMR_IA_4CMR2_12present_item[] = "\n        Presents a single item (or distractor) to the model by updating the\n        feature vector. Also provides options to update context and the model's\n        associative matrices after presentation. [Modified by Beige]\n\n        :param item_idx: The index of the cell within the feature vector that\n            should be activated by the presented item. If None, presents an\n            empty feature vector.\n        :param source: If None, no source features will be activated. If a 1D\n            array, the source features in the feature vector will be set to\n            match the numbers in the source array.\n        :param update_context: If True, the context vector will update after\n            the feature vector has been updated. If False, the feature vector\n            will update but the context vector will not change.\n        :param update_weights: If True, the model's weight matrices will update\n            to strengthen the association between the presented item and the\n            state of context at the time of presentation. If False, no learning\n            will occur after item presentation.\n        ";

 0883:         """
 0884:         Presents a single item (or distractor) to the model by updating the
 0885:         feature vector. Also provides options to update context and the model's
 0886:         associative matrices after presentation. [Modified by Beige]
 0887: 
 0888:         :param item_idx: The index of the cell within the feature vector that
 0889:             should be activated by the presented item. If None, presents an
 0890:             empty feature vector.
 0891:         :param source: If None, no source features will be activated. If a 1D
 0892:             array, the source features in the feature vector will be set to
 0893:             match the numbers in the source array.
 0894:         :param update_context: If True, the context vector will update after
 0895:             the feature vector has been updated. If False, the feature vector
 0896:             will update but the context vector will not change.
 0897:         :param update_weights: If True, the model's weight matrices will update
 0898:             to strengthen the association between the presented item and the

+1504: def run_cmr2_single_sess(params, pres_mat, sem_mat, source_mat=None, mode='IFR'):

static char __pyx_doc_6CMR_IA_8run_cmr2_single_sess[] = "\n    Simulates a single session of free recall using the specified parameter set.\n    [Unchanged from CMR2]\n\n    :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the\n        simulation. Call the CMR2_pack_cyth.make_params() function to get a\n        dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.\n    :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be\n        presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number\n        of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to\n        range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity\n        matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to\n        zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length.\n    :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all\n        words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must\n        match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along\n        row k-1 and column k-1.\n    :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat\n        should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The\n        matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial\n        position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source\n        features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the\n        kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)\n    :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'IFR'\n        for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall. (DEFUALT='IFR')\n\n    :returns: Two 2D arrays. The first contains the ID numbers of the items the model\n        recalled on each trial. The second contains the response times of each"" of\n        those items relative to the start of the recall period.\n    ";

 1505:     """
 1506:     Simulates a single session of free recall using the specified parameter set.
 1507:     [Unchanged from CMR2]
 1508: 
 1509:     :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the
 1510:         simulation. Call the CMR2_pack_cyth.make_params() function to get a
 1511:         dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.
 1512:     :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be
 1513:         presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number
 1514:         of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to
 1515:         range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity
 1516:         matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to
 1517:         zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length.
 1518:     :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all
 1519:         words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must
 1520:         match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along
 1521:         row k-1 and column k-1.
 1522:     :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat
 1523:         should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The
 1524:         matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial
 1525:         position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source
 1526:         features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the
 1527:         kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)
 1528:     :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'IFR'
 1529:         for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall. (DEFUALT='IFR')
 1530: 
 1531:     :returns: Two 2D arrays. The first contains the ID numbers of the items the model
 1532:         recalled on each trial. The second contains the response times of each of
 1533:         those items relative to the start of the recall period.
 1534:     """

static char __pyx_doc_6CMR_IA_10run_cmr2_multi_sess[] = "\n    Simulates multiple sessions of free recall using a single set of parameters.\n    [Unchanged from CMR2]\n\n    :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the\n        simulation. Call the CMR2_pack_cyth.make_params() function to get a\n        dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.\n    :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be\n        presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number\n        of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to\n        range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity\n        matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to\n        zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length.\n    :param identifiers: A 1D array of session numbers, subject IDs, or other values\n        indicating how the rows/trials in pres_mat and source_mat should be divided up\n        into sessions. For example, one could simulate two four-trial sessions by\n        setting identifiers to np.array([0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1]), specifying that the\n        latter four trials come from a different session than the first four trials.\n    :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all\n        words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must\n        match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along\n        row k-1 and column k-1.\n    :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat\n        should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The\n        matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial\n        position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source\n        features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the"" value of the\n        kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)\n    :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'IFR'\n        for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall. (DEFUALT='IFR')\n\n    :returns: Two 2D arrays. The first contains the ID numbers of the items the model\n        recalled on each trial. The second contains the response times of each of\n        those items relative to the start of the recall period.\n    ";

 1562:     """
 1563:     Simulates multiple sessions of free recall using a single set of parameters.
 1564:     [Unchanged from CMR2]
 1565: 
 1566:     :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the
 1567:         simulation. Call the CMR2_pack_cyth.make_params() function to get a
 1568:         dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.
 1569:     :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be
 1570:         presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number
 1571:         of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to
 1572:         range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity
 1573:         matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to
 1574:         zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length.
 1575:     :param identifiers: A 1D array of session numbers, subject IDs, or other values
 1576:         indicating how the rows/trials in pres_mat and source_mat should be divided up
 1577:         into sessions. For example, one could simulate two four-trial sessions by
 1578:         setting identifiers to np.array([0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1]), specifying that the
 1579:         latter four trials come from a different session than the first four trials.
 1580:     :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all
 1581:         words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must
 1582:         match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along
 1583:         row k-1 and column k-1.
 1584:     :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat
 1585:         should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The
 1586:         matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial
 1587:         position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source
 1588:         features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the
 1589:         kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)
 1590:     :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'IFR'
 1591:         for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall. (DEFUALT='IFR')
 1592: 
 1593:     :returns: Two 2D arrays. The first contains the ID numbers of the items the model
 1594:         recalled on each trial. The second contains the response times of each of
 1595:         those items relative to the start of the recall period.
 1596:     """
+1597:     now_test = time.time()

 1627: # def run_peers_recog_multi_sess(params, data_dict, sem_mat, source_mat=None, task='Recog', mode='Final'):
 1628: #     """
 1629: #     Simulates multiple sessions of peers recognition using a single set of parameters.
 1630: #     [Newly added by Beige]
 1631: #
 1632: #     :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the
 1633: #         simulation. Call the CMR_IA.make_params() function to get a
 1634: #         dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.
 1635: #     :param data_dict: a dictionary contains pres_mat, rec_mat, ffr_mat, cue_mat.
 1636: #     :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all
 1637: #         words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must
 1638: #         match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along
 1639: #         row k-1 and column k-1.
 1640: #     :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat
 1641: #         should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The
 1642: #         matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial
 1643: #         position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source
 1644: #         features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the
 1645: #         kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)
 1646: #     :param task: Recognition. (DEFAULT='Recog')
 1647: #     :param mode: A string indicating the type of recognition to simulate. Set to 'Final'
 1648: #         for PEERS recognition. (DEFUALT='IFR')
 1649: #
 1650: #     :returns: Three dictionaries. The first contains the recognition response for each item.
 1651: #         The second contains the reaction time for each response. The third contains the
 1652: #         simulated context similarity for each item.
 1653: #     """
 1654: #     now_test = time.time()
 1655: #
 1656: #     recog_dict = {}
 1657: #     rt_dict = {}
 1658: #     csim_dict = {}
 1659: #

Call the CMR_IA.make_params() function to get a\n        dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.\n    :param df: A dataframe of experiment design. This dataframe should have these\n        3 columns: \"session\", \"position\", \"itemno\". Each row corresponds to a trial.\n        \"session\" specifies the session, \"position\" specifies the sequence of items\n        within a session, and \"itemno\" specifies which item is presented. \"itemno\" should\n        correspond to sem_mat.\n    :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all\n        words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must\n        match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along\n        row k-1 and column k-1.\n    :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat\n        should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The\n        matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial\n        position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source\n        features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the\n        kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)\n    :param task: Recognition. (DEFAULT='Recog')\n    :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'Continuous'\n        for continuous recognition. (DEFUALT='Continuous')\n\n    :returns: A dataframe with 6 columns: \"session\", \"position\", \"itemno\", \"s_resp\", \"s_rt\", \"csim\".\n        The first three columns are identical to those in input df. The last three columns\n        indicates the simulated response, r""eaction time and context similarity respectively.\n    ";

 1793:     """
 1794:     Simulates multiple sessions of continuous recognition using a single set of parameters.
 1795:     [Newly added by Beige]
 1796: 
 1797:     :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the
 1798:         simulation. Call the CMR_IA.make_params() function to get a
 1799:         dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.
 1800:     :param df: A dataframe of experiment design. This dataframe should have these
 1801:         3 columns: "session", "position", "itemno". Each row corresponds to a trial.
 1802:         "session" specifies the session, "position" specifies the sequence of items
 1803:         within a session, and "itemno" specifies which item is presented. "itemno" should
 1804:         correspond to sem_mat.
 1805:     :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all
 1806:         words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must
 1807:         match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along
 1808:         row k-1 and column k-1.
 1809:     :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat
 1810:         should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The
 1811:         matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial
 1812:         position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source
 1813:         features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the
 1814:         kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)
 1815:     :param task: Recognition. (DEFAULT='Recog')
 1816:     :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'Continuous'
 1817:         for continuous recognition. (DEFUALT='Continuous')
 1818: 
 1819:     :returns: A dataframe with 6 columns: "session", "position", "itemno", "s_resp", "s_rt", "csim".
 1820:         The first three columns are identical to those in input df. The last three columns
 1821:         indicates the simulated response, reaction time and context similarity respectively.
 1822:     """

Call the CMR_IA.make_params() function to get a\n        dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.\n    :param df: A dataframe of experiment design. This dataframe should have these\n        3 columns: \"session\", \"position\", \"itemno\". Each row corresponds to a trial.\n        \"session\" specifies the session, \"position\" specifies the sequence of items\n        within a session, and \"itemno\" specifies which item is presented. \"itemno\" should\n        correspond to sem_mat.\n    :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all\n        words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must\n        match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along\n        row k-1 and column k-1.\n    :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat\n        should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The\n        matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial\n        position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source\n        features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the\n        kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)\n    :param task: Recognition. (DEFAULT='Recog')\n    :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'Continuous'\n        for continuous recognition. (DEFUALT='Continuous')\n\n    :returns: A dataframe with 6 columns: \"session\", \"position\", \"itemno\", \"s_resp\", \"s_rt\", \"csim\".\n        The first three columns are identical to those in input df. The last three columns\n        indicates the simulated response, react""ion time and context similarity respectively.\n    ";

 1858:     """
 1859:     Simulates multiple sessions of successive testing using a single set of parameters.
 1860:     [Newly added by Beige]
 1861: 
 1862:     :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the
 1863:         simulation. Call the CMR_IA.make_params() function to get a
 1864:         dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.
 1865:     :param df: A dataframe of experiment design. This dataframe should have these
 1866:         3 columns: "session", "position", "itemno". Each row corresponds to a trial.
 1867:         "session" specifies the session, "position" specifies the sequence of items
 1868:         within a session, and "itemno" specifies which item is presented. "itemno" should
 1869:         correspond to sem_mat.
 1870:     :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all
 1871:         words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must
 1872:         match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along
 1873:         row k-1 and column k-1.
 1874:     :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat
 1875:         should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The
 1876:         matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial
 1877:         position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source
 1878:         features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the
 1879:         kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)
 1880:     :param task: Recognition. (DEFAULT='Recog')
 1881:     :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'Continuous'
 1882:         for continuous recognition. (DEFUALT='Continuous')
 1883: 
 1884:     :returns: A dataframe with 6 columns: "session", "position", "itemno", "s_resp", "s_rt", "csim".
 1885:         The first three columns are identical to those in input df. The last three columns
 1886:         indicates the simulated response, reaction time and context similarity respectively.
 1887:     """
